{XPPMATH 20 "6+\"\"\"\"\")\"#G\"#c\"#qF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6,\"\"\"\"\"*\"#O\"#%)\"$E\"F'F&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "
" {XPPMATH 20 "6-\"\"\"\"#5\"#X\"$?\"\"$5#\"$_#F'F&F%F$F#" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 25 "Pascall's Triangle(above)" }}}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 8 "Compute " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "sum(binomial(n,k),k=0..n)" 
"6#-%$sumG6$-%)binomialG6$%\"nG%\"kG/F*;\"\"!F)" }{TEXT -1 34 "  for n
=1 to 10.  Here the symbol " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "Sigma;" "6#%&SigmaG" }
{TEXT -1 70 " (Greek letter Sigma) stands for sum.   (See the workshee
t SumSeq.mws)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT 258 286 "What general formula do the above calculations in  sugg
est?  \"Sequence\" tells Maple to pull the coefficients out & put in o
rder (a+1) to the power (0 to 10).  This also included the program bei
ng told that as the power changes, so does the line that the coefficie
nts we want it to pull." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 388 "2.  Pascal's Triangle.  Recall the definition of Pa
scal's Triangle.   Use Maple to construct the first 10 rows of Pascal'
s Triangle. (The trick will be to get the coefficients to occur in the
 correct order.  The Maple command for generating a sequence might be \+
helpful. It is   seq(expression(i),i=m..n);   where expression(i) is a
n expression with index i and m..n is a range of numbers." }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 3 "   " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 24 "Se
e Above Please!!!!!!!!" }}{PARA 8 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 31 "Error, missing \+
operator or `;`\n" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 214 "3.  Functions.  In this exericse we study the basic prop
erties of polynomials and rational functions.  Some revelant MAPLE com
mands will be   factor, expand, solve, fsolve, denom, numer, simplify,
 subs,   ....... ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 171 "     The first thi
ng we need to learn is how to define a function.  There are two ways, \+
each with its own advantages and disadvantages.  First define the poly
nomial p1 as " }{TEXT 282 2 "a " }{TEXT -1 1 "s" }{TEXT 283 23 "ymboli
c expression in x" }{TEXT -1 119 " in the following way:    p1:=x^2-1;
  (Note the colon before the =, this is always required when defining \+
something.)  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "p1:=x^2-1;
" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p1G,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F*F*!\"
\"" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 "  \+
   Now define the same polynomial as " }{TEXT 281 30 "an operation on \+
the variable x" }{TEXT -1 40 " in the following way:     p2:=x->x^2-1;
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 13 "p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p2Gf*6#%\"
xG6\"6$%)operatorG%&arrowGF(,&*$)9$\"\"#\"\"\"F1F1!\"\"F(F(F(" }}}
{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 257 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 190 "Try \+
the following command sequences to see some of the differences in how \+
MAPLE  treats these two definitions.  As always record your observatio
ns and comments on the worksheet in text mode." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "p1;" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F(F(!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "p2;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 
"6#%#p2G" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 6 "p2(x);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)%\"xG\"
\"#\"\"\"F(F(!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 8 "p2(t-3
);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$),&%\"tG\"\"\"\"\"$!\"\"\"\"
#F(F(F(F*" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "p2(u^3-u^2+2);
" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$),(*$)%\"uG\"\"$\"\"\"F+*$)F)
\"\"#F+!\"\"F.F+F.F+F+F+F/" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "     " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 255 "     This works just like we expect subs
titution to work because p2 is an operation on whatever is in the (  )
.  However since p1 is a symbolic expression we have some difficulties
 with substituting into it directly.   Try the following command seque
nces." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 6 "p1(x);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)-%\"xG6
#F'\"\"#\"\"\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 8 "p
1(t-3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)-%\"xG6#,&%\"tG\"\"\"
\"\"$!\"\"\"\"#F+F+F+F-" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "
p1(u^3-u^2+2);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)-%\"xG6#,(*$)%
\"uG\"\"$\"\"\"F.*$)F,\"\"#F.!\"\"F1F.F1F.F.F.F2" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 135 "      Notice the extra x
 in front.  This is curious and not very reassuring.  To substitute in
to a symbolic expression we must use the " }{TEXT 284 4 "subs" }{TEXT 
-1 9 " command." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "subs(x=t-3,p1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
20 "6#,&*$),&%\"tG\"\"\"\"\"$!\"\"\"\"#F(F(F(F*" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "subs(x=6,p1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 
"6#\"#N" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 6 "p2(6);" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"#N" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "    " }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 75 "     Now let's do some simple operations
 on this polynomial.  In each case " }{TEXT 277 46 "Explain what the c
ommand appears to have done." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 11 "factor(p1);" }{TEXT -1 17 "I
t factored x^2-1" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&!
\"\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 25 "It is just \+
factoring out." }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 11 "factor(p2
);" }{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "You must tell it to \+
factor for x. It didn't know what to do for p2." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
