" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 280 111 
"Why do you think high school students are never asked to remember the
 general formula for the roots of a cubic?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 33 "Because it is way toooooo Long!!!" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
113 "4.  Solving Equations in One Variable.   There are two different \+
commands to direct Maple to solve an equation:  " }{TEXT 285 5 "solve
" }{TEXT -1 5 " and " }{TEXT 286 7 "fsolve." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 35 "They have different purposes.  The " }{TEXT 287 5 "solve" }
{TEXT -1 63 " command attempts to find exact solutions.  If the expres
sion  " }{TEXT 289 1 "f" }{TEXT -1 116 "  is defined in terms of only \+
one variable, there are several different ways to direct Maple to solv
e the equation  " }{TEXT 290 5 "f  = " }{TEXT 291 4 "0.  " }{TEXT -1 
54 "The following all cause Maple to solve the equation   " }{TEXT 
292 5 "f  = " }{TEXT 293 2 "0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 16 "       solve(f);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f,x);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "      \+
 solve(f=0);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 20 "       solve(f=0,x);" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 349 "Maple ma
kes an assumption that if the coefficients of a polynomial are all giv
en exactly (as integers or rational numbers [ratios of integer]), then
 you are only interested in finding exact solutions.  The Fundamental \+
Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee that the solutions of  a polynomi
al can be found exactly, only the polynomial has solutions.  " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 78 "You can f
orce Maple to report additional (approximate) solutions by using the \+
" }{TEXT 288 6 "fsolve" }{TEXT -1 45 " command.  (What does the \"f\" \+
stand for?)  In" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "addition, to forcing \+
Maple to report approximate solutions, you can specify a field extensi
on (typically real or complex) and require Maple to look for solutions
 which fit in that field extension.  Also, one can specify a range of \+
x values and force" }{TEXT 296 7 " fsolve" }{TEXT -1 75 " to only look
 for solutions in that specified range.  For example, compare:" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
16 "fsolve(4*x-x^3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6%$!+++++?!\"*$
\"\"!F'$\"+++++?F%" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 23 "fsolve(4*x-x^3,x=1..4);" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#$\"+++++?!\"*" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "For each of the polynomia
ls " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p[1]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"\"\"" }{TEXT -1 9 " through " 
}{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p[14]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"#9" }{TEXT -1 19 ", do the followi
ng:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "     a.   solve for all exact root
s whereever possible, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 59 "     b.   find \+
all approximate roots to 10 decimal places, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 43 "     c.  factor each into linear factors.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 106 "You will need to click o
