" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "5.  Solving Systems of Equations in S
everal Variables.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 49 "When we have an equation in two variables, e.g.  " }
{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x -2*y = 5" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"y
GF'!\"\"\"\"&" }{TEXT -1 147 "  we often associate with it a graph, th
e set of points (x,y) in the two-dimensional plane which satisfy the e
quation.  For a linear equation like " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x-2*y = 5" "6
#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"yGF'!\"\"\"\"&" }{TEXT -1 89 " t
he graph is a straight line.  For more a complicated equation in two v
ariables, e.g.,  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "2*x^3 -3*x + y^2 = x*y" "6#/,(*&\"
\"#\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"$F'F'*&F*F'F)F'!\"\"*$%\"yGF&F'*&F)F'F.F'" }{TEXT 
-1 45 "  the graph becomes a more complicated curve." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 282 "When we have two equat
ions in two variables, we think of the solution set of this system of \+
equations as being the set of points (x,y) which satisfy both equation
s simultaneously.  In terms of their graphs, the solution set is the s
et of points where the graphs intersect (cross).  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 622 "When we have two linear \+
equations in two variables, since their graphs are straight lines, the
n two straight lines, if they cross, will cross in exactly one place. \+
 Hence, the solution set of the system of equations will be exactly on
e point (x,y).  If we have two equations which are more complicated, t
hen the number of intersection points (crossing points) of their graph
s can vary.  For example, if the graph of one equation is a circle and
 the graph of the other equation is a straight line, then, if their gr
aphs cross, then number of solutions (intersection points) of the syst
em of equations could be 1 or 2.  Etc." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 128 "We can instruct Maple to find soluti
ons of systems of equations using the solve or fsolve commands.  The s
yntax for doing so is:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 30 "     solve( \{eq1,eq2\}, \{x,y\});" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 85 "where eq1 and eq2 are \+
equations in the variables x and y.  This is illustrated below." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
42 "solve(\{ x + 2*y = 5, 2*x-3*y = -1\},\{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "
" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<$/%\"yG#\"#6\"\"(/%\"xG#\"#8F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 22 "We could have defined " }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 40 "eq1 := x + 2*y = 5;\neq2 := \+
2*x-3*y = -1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%$eq1G/,&%\"xG\"\"\"
*&\"\"#F(%\"yGF(F(\"\"&" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%$eq2G/,&*
&\"\"#\"\"\"%\"xGF)F)*&\"\"$F)%\"yGF)!\"\"F." }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 26 "and then given the comman
d" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 25 "solve( \{eq1,eq2\}, \{x,y\})
;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<$/%\"yG#\"#6\"\"(/%\"xG#\"#8F(" 
}}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 55 "and ac
hieved the same result.  Remember the solution  (" }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "13/
7" "6#*&\"#8\"\"\"\"\"(!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 2 ", " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "11/7" "
6#*&\"#6\"\"\"\"\"(!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 127 ") represents a point in the t
wo-dimensional plane (why two-dimensional?) where the graphs of the eq
uations intersect (cross).  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 63 "Find the solutions, if they exist, for the foll
